 Han Suk-kyu and the Gendered Cultural Economy of Stardom and Fandom -- tPart V Shifting Contexts, Changing Fan Cultures From Concert Halls to Console Games -- t17 Loving Music Listeners, Entertainments, and the Origins of Music Fandom in Nineteenth-Century America -- t18 Girls Allowed? The Marginalization of Female Sport Fans -- t19 Customer Relationship Management: Automating Fandom in Music Communities -- t20 Playing the Game: Performance in Digital Game Audiences -- tPart VI Fans and Anti-Fans: From Love to Hate -- t21 Fan-tagonism: Factions, Institutions, and Constitutive Hegemonies of Fandom -- t22 Untidy: Fan Response to the Soiling of Martha Stewart’s Spotless Image -- t23 The Anti-Fan within the Fan: Awe and Envy in Sport Fandom -- t24 A Vacancy at the Paris Hilton -- t25 The Other Side of Fandom: Anti-Fans, Non-Fans, and the Hurts of History -- t26 Afterword: The Future of Fandom -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are all fans. Whether we log on to Web sites to scrutinize the latest plot turns in Lost, “stalk” our favorite celebrities on Gawker, attend gaming conventions, or simply wait with bated breath for the newest Harry Potter novel-each of us is a fan. Fandom extends beyond television and film to literature, opera, sports, and pop music, and encompasses both high and low culture. Fandom brings together leading scholars to examine fans, their practices, and their favorite texts. This unparalleled selection of original essays examines instances across the spectrum of modern cultural consumption from Karl Marx to Paris Hilton, Buffy the Vampire Slayer to backyard wrestling, Bach fugues to Bollywood cinema¸ and nineteenth-century concert halls to computer gaming. Contributors examine fans of high cultural texts and genres, the spaces of fandom, fandom around the globe, the impact of new technologies on fandom, and the legal and historical contexts of fan activity. Fandom is key to understanding modern life in our increasingly mediated and globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFans (Persons). 0aPopular culturexPsychological aspects. 0aSubculture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aFandom.  aglobalized.  aincreasingly.  alife.  amediated.  amodern.  aunderstanding.  aworld.1 aAlters, Diane F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagnall, Gaynor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielby, Denise D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBird, S. Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooker, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkart, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavicchi, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Bertha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiecko, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClick, Melissa A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouldry, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawford, Garry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosling, Victoria K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarrington, C. Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrington, C. Lee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/